Read in the original datafiles

# to print this chunk, but not execute it again once the files are imported, add: eval=FALSE
# use the haven package to read in the data -- we need the MIDUS II data and the biomarker project data
midus2 <- read_spss("04652-0001-Data.sav")
bio <- read_spss("29282-0001-Data.sav")
# save as rds files because importing SPSS files is really slow
saveRDS(midus2, "midus2.rds")
saveRDS(bio, "bio.rds")

Read in the saved datafiles

midus2 <- readRDS("midus2.rds")
bio <- readRDS("bio.rds")

Subset the datafiles

# subset midus to keep only people in the main sample (SAMPLMAJ) who have complete data on scales and demo vars
midus2subset <- midus2 %>% filter(SAMPLMAJ ==1 ) %>% select(M2ID, B1PRSEX, B1PF7A, (contains("B1SE6")), B1PAGE_M2, B1SE7I, B1SE7T, B1SE7BB, B1SE7EE, B1SNEURO, B1SEXTRA, B1SOPEN, B1SCONS2, B1SAGREE, B1SMPQAG) %>%  filter(complete.cases(B1SNEURO, B1SEXTRA, B1SOPEN, B1SCONS2, B1SAGREE, B1SMPQAG, B1PRSEX, B1PAGE_M2, B1PF7A)) %>%  mutate(IN_MIDUS2 = 1)
bio.subset <- bio %>% select(M2ID, (contains("B4Q4")), (contains("B4Q5")), (contains("B4Q6")), B4QTA_AG, B4QTA_AT, B4QTA_AR, B4QAE_AI, B4QAE_AO, B4QAE_AC) %>% filter(complete.cases(B4QTA_AG, B4QTA_AT, B4QTA_AR, B4QAE_AI, B4QAE_AO, B4QAE_AC)) %>%  mutate(IN_BIO =1)
# Conduct left join to merge midus2 and bio, but keep only cases that are in our midus2subset (if in bio.subset but not midus2subset, remove them), then reo-order to put vars of most interest up front
combine <- dplyr::left_join(midus2subset, bio.subset, by="M2ID") %>% select(M2ID, B1PF7A, B1SNEURO, B1SAGREE, B1SEXTRA, B1SOPEN, B1SCONS2, B4QTA_AG, B4QTA_AT, B4QTA_AR, B4QAE_AI, B4QAE_AO, B4QAE_AC, B1SMPQAG, B1PAGE_M2, B1PRSEX, (everything()))
# put everything function at the end = everything before it will be at the front of the dataset

create dataset for analysis

# rename combine as analyze 
analyze <- combine
# note which variables are categorical and numeric and tidy things up
# names returns a full list of variabe names
all.vars <- names(analyze)
#cat.vars is a list with two items, both of which are categorical/factor
cat.vars <- c("M2ID", "B1PF7A")
# mutate_at() applies one operations to a set of variables (.vars: list of vars to be mutated, .tbl: data, .funs: a list of functions to be applied)
# as.numeric() forces variable type to be numeric, as.factor() forces variable type to be factor type
# vars(all.vars) with as.numeric tells R to make ALL variables in the dataset to be numeric
# vars(cat.vats) with as.factor just changes these two factor variables to be recognized as factors
# Then creating a new variable called gender
# Then create a dummy variable called Male, which is 0 (so all males = 0, females = 1). Then delete B1PRSEX, so Male is now the only coded gender variable, and we have another variable that labels with words.  
analyze <- analyze %>% 
  mutate_at(vars(all.vars), funs(as.numeric)) %>% 
  mutate_at(vars(cat.vars), funs(as.factor)) %>% 
  mutate(GENDER = factor(B1PRSEX, levels = c("1", "2"), labels = c("male", "female"))) %>%
  mutate(MALE = B1PRSEX - 1) %>%
  select(-B1PRSEX)
# create subset of just variable scale scores and the demographic variables
analyze <- analyze %>%  
  select(B1SNEURO, B1SAGREE, B1SEXTRA, B1SOPEN, B1SCONS2,  
         B4QTA_AG, B4QTA_AT, B4QTA_AR, B4QAE_AI, B4QAE_AO, B4QAE_AC,
         B1SMPQAG,
         B1PF7A,
         B1PAGE_M2, 
         GENDER, MALE)

Set hypotheses

# I am interested in assessing the relationship between agreeableness and anger expression out. In this case, I am not particularly interested in a significance test for the intercept, its the slope that is of interest. I will state a null and alternative hypothesis for the slope.
# My null hypothesis: B1 (the regression slope) is equal to 0
# My alterntive hypothesis: B1 is not equal to 0

Set alpha and obtain the critical value of t

# I am going to set alpha to .05, and use a 2 tailed test. For a SLR, the df equals n - 1 - # of predictors, so n-2, or 1761 - 2 = 1759 for my case.
qt(c(.025, .975), df=625)
[1] -1.963767  1.963767
# remember, df here is N-2 (N-1-# predictors)
# The critical value of t for this model is 1.964. If t-star is either greater than 1.964 or less than -1.964 then I will reject the null hypothesis.

Center agreeableness at the mean and then fit the SLR

# From the descriptive statistics above, we see that agreeableness ranges from 1.8 to 4, so 0 isnt an observed value for this variable. Since the intercept of our SLR will represent the predicted value of y, when x equals 0, we should create a meaningful value of 0 for x. To do this, I will center at the mean.
myvars <- myvars %>% 
  mutate(B1SAGREE_m = B1SAGREE - mean(B1SAGREE))
my_model <- lm(B4QAE_AO ~ B1SAGREE_m, data = myvars) 
  
ols_regress(my_model)

                                   Parameter Estimates

      model      Beta    Std. Error    Std. Beta       t        Sig      lower     upper 
-----------------------------------------------------------------------------------------
(Intercept)    12.933         0.127                 101.720    0.000    12.683    13.183 
 B1SAGREE_m    -0.851         0.246       -0.137     -3.456    0.001    -1.334    -0.367 
-----------------------------------------------------------------------------------------
# Output interpretations:
  # The intercept is 12.933. This is the predicted anger-expression-out score for individuals with the mean score for agreeableness. The slope is -.851. This is the expected change in anger-expression-out for a one unit increase in agreeableness.
#The t-star is of the slope is -3.456 (slope estimate/std error). This means that our estimate of the slope is 3.456 standard errors away from the asserted null hypothesis (0). If the null hypothesis were true, we would expect about 95% of the random samples to produce an estimate of the slope that is within 1.964 standard errors of 0. Therefore it is highly unlikely that the null hypothesis is true given this estimate of the slope. In other words, the abslute value of t-star (3.456) is greater than the absolute value of t-crit (1.964). In fact, the p-value = .001, which provides the probability that we would obtain a t-star of this magnitude or larger if the null hypothesis were true. Therefore, we reject the null hypothesis.
# The 95% CI is -1.334 to -0.367. Based on the sampling distribution, we expect that 95% of the 95% CIs that we would construct across many, many random samples would contain the population slope. We can think of the 95% CI as giving us a range of plausible values for the parameter estimate and showing us the precision of our estimate. The fact that 0 is not inside the 95% CI corresponds with our t-test, that is, 0 is not likely to be a plausible value for the slope.
# It seems that agreeableness is significantly associated with anger-expression-out. Higher scores on agreeableness are associated with lower scores on anger-expression-out. Agreeableness predicts 1.9% of the variance in anger-expression-out (R-squared). In a SLR, the standardized beta is equal to the correlation, so the correlation between agreeableness and ager-expression-out is -.137.

Create scatterplot of neuroticim and aggression with fitted model

temp_var <- predict(my_model, myvars, interval="prediction")
myvars_new <- cbind(temp_var, myvars)
ggplot(myvars_new, aes(x = B1SAGREE_m, y =B4QAE_AO)) +
  geom_jitter() +
  geom_smooth(method = "lm", se = TRUE) +
  geom_line(aes(y=lwr), color = "red", linetype = "dashed") +
  geom_line(aes(y=upr), color = "red", linetype = "dashed") +
  labs(title = "Scatterplot of Agreebleness and Anger-Expression-Out with Best Fit Line",
       subtitle = "Confidence Interval in Gray Shaded Area, Prediction Interval in Red", 
       x = "Agreeableness (centered at the mean)", y = "Anger-Expression-Out")

Create graph of residuals

myvars <- myvars %>% 
  add_residuals(my_model) 
  
ggplot(myvars, aes(x = resid)) + geom_histogram(binwidth = .5)
